<font color="#FF0000">REPLIES &amp; THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 17  3:18:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Doc, JJ, Arthur, Sarah, Nurse Ratchet, Dr. Spatz et al.,<br><br>
1. Haven't been able to get on line for over a week.  If my post was one of those that helped give the impression of an intellectual game in progress; I'm sorry if I got too philosophical.  It's not a game with me by any means.  While  being fortunate to have pretty muched escaped PTSD; I've come to know too many walking wounded over the years to take the matter lightly.  Some guys still have flashbacks these days, and my VVA chapter lost its second member due to suicide in 10 years of existence.  As an Aerial Surveillance Officer, who spent most of his time in the rear; I won't claim to have had any horrendous experiences (shot at only once in 39 air missions by the enemy and twice by our own artiilery along with the regular nuisance mortaring and probing of the base).  I try to make myself useful in the Veterans' community, and help those who need it.<br><br>
2. In Nov. '62, I was a high school senior in Milwauke when Kennedy called up the Wisconsin National Guard during the Berlin crisis.  Kruchschev's shoe pounding at the UN was still a vivid memory.  I would be 18 in February.  This was a wake up call for anyone my age; especially with all the reminders to register for the draft.  Over the next 10 months, I came to the conclusion that we were going to get into a war someplace, that I would wind up in it, and that it would be better to go in as an officer than as an enlisted man.  So when the ROTC made their pitch to the incoming freshmen males at UWM (this being before protests caused universities to pull the plug); I signed right up.  Thought things would blow up in Germany or Cuba though.  Vietnam was barely on the radar scope. As for my family; my father agreed with my choice, but was rather hurt that I didn't consult him first.  He had served as a radar mechanic in WWII.  My maternal grandfather &amp; my Dad's brother-in-law<br>
werer also vets.  At Notre Dame High, we got literature from the Christian Anti-Communist Crusade in Sociology, and heard  much on the domino theory during my first years of college.  Anti-war feeling wasn't a factor on what was basically a streetcar campus till spring '67.  By that time I was committed.  If I dropped out of school; it would have meant immediate induction into the Army as a private per the contract signed in Sept. '65 at the start of my junior year.<br>
This is how one guy got into the war.  I'm not about to second guess myself using 20-20 hindsight, and I think there has been a bit too much second guessing of others this way.<br>
I don't believe on balance we should have gotten into the war in Vietnam, but I don't believe all our motives were bad either; though our knowledge and understanding of the situation was appallingly faulty.  Our leaders who had come of age during WWII had a fatal arrogant blindness to the limits of their personal abilities and wisdom to bring the resources of this country to bear on any problem. Yet I have absolutely no illusions that the Vietnamese Communists were the angelic agrarian reformers pictured by the American Left.  Then again some of our allies, like the Vietnamese National Police, were no angels either.  All in all my feelings are a bit conflicted.  Last Veterans' day, a Vietnamese Veterans Group had a prominent booth near the Vietnam Memorial in DC, and made a point of thanking every Amarican veteran that went by.  What do those of you who are protesters have to say to men who spent 6, 8 or 10 years in &quot;reeducation camps&quot;?  Most of them weren't &quot;colonial lackeys&quot;.  Many are &quot;ethnic Chinese&quot;, who became unwelcome after the fall of the South.<br><br>
3.  Lest it be forgotten, anti-war protesters weren't the only people rough on returning soldiers.  Many Vietnam Vets were treated like dirt at many a VFW or American Legion Post for years; because they &quot;lost&quot; the war. Only membership loss through increasing mortality due to age and the resignations in protest by fathers of Vietnam Vets turned that around in the early '80s.<br><br>
4.  To Sarah:  I don't mean the form of government in Kuwait  is &quot;irrelevant&quot; in a moral sense.  But by either traditional Middle Eastern Islamic or modern Western standards, it is definately 100% above Hussein's dictatorship.  Yes, and I know we probably would have treated Saddams' invasion just like we treated Suharto's of East Timor without the incentive of oil.  But the fact remains that the invasion in and of itself and not whether the government of Kuwait would change is &quot;relevant&quot; to the prosecution of the Gulf War.  That said, I will try to stay on Vietnam; because a person could bury the site under peripheral issues that may be very important and even philosophically related, but would ultimately dilute the focus of this site too much.<br><br>
4. Since many anti-war protesters were female (on my campus, it appeared to be about half); I have to say, that even with a very small number of altruistic males, at least a bare majority were not concerned with saving their own necks.  Oh yes, after nearly 30 years, I still vividly remember being one of those singled out to get a daisy placed in his rifle at the May '67 Chancellor's Review, and saying to the girl, &quot;Just don't dare grab the weapon.&quot;  Fortunately, none did.
<p><code>-- turtle@plantaganet.com  (Gerald Ney, &quot;the Herd&quot; 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


